<br>
okay.<br>
<br>
You said this: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A failure by a reusable nuclear booster is also quite spectacular, but could also result in the release of radioactive fallout into the environment equal to the output of an entire nations nuclear power plants.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Prove it to me.<br>
<br>
I have stated in my first post that Chernobyl, ONE REACTOR, released conservatively 9,500 kilograms of intensely radioactive core material.   (I will keep it simple and stick to weight released, becquerels make my head hurt.)<br>
<br>
Let's pick the USSR as our nation, since you did not specify.<br>
<br>
 Further, let's only pick their terribly designed graphite moderated plants, of which 6 were planned for the Chernobyl plant.  According to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nti.org/db/nisprofs/russia/tables/rupowtab.htm"> this page, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> Russia has another 13, for a total of 19. <br>
<br>
So, assume 19 times 9500 kilograms of radioactive materials are released by a PARTIAL release of one nations reactors.  This is a total of 180,500 kilograms of CORE material, the most active stuff imaginable.<br>
<br>
Please explain in detail the scenario where a single nuclear powered heavy-lift booster could release 180,500 kilos of core material.  (It'd have to be one BIG mother. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   )<br>
<br>
Facts.  They're a bear.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 762<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/5/02 10:44:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which is safer? Flying chernobyls or big fireworks</span><hr size=1> You are confusing core mass with radioactivity.<br>
 <br>
90+% of a powerplant core is essentially inert heavey metal (heavier then lead). This metal is of extremeley low specific activity.<br>
<br>
It is the FISSION PRODUCTS that are the fallout. <br>
These measure in the pounds rather then tons.<br>
<br>
A 2-3 gigawatt(thermal) nuclear power reactor at equilibrium contains ~15 billion curies of fission and decay products.<br>
<br>
You have neglected two points.<br>
1) A nuclear engine uses U235 at a 90%+ enrichment versus the few percent of a power reactor.<br>
2) Nuclear engines are run at a tremendously higher power density then any power plant.<br>
<br>
A 2.5 million pound thrust nuclear engine (or cluster) runs at 45 gigawatts thermal and contains at equilibrium more than TWENTY times the fallout products. (and is unshielded and without containment)<br>
<br>
<br>
These are FACTS.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
