 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udrcarstairs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/6/02 12:52:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.imgstudio.com/2002/March/28/stamp_lthumb/032820021216063.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Answers</span><hr size=1> ArkuunAves asked some questions, and I don’t think anyone answered them. So, despite not being the best person to do so, I will attempt to answer them. If I make any glaring errors, please feel free to jump in and correct me.<br>
<br>
Question 1: How do you plan on decontaminating the craft?<br>
        We don’t. Once launched, an Orion type craft is not intended to ever land. I guess it could, theoretically, especially on an airless body, but it really isn’t envisioned to do so. <br>
<br>
Question 2: Stress limits?<br>
        This was researched in depth by the original development team, and they felt the problem surmountable using 1960’s technology and materials. Their models functioned as or better than predicted, and materials that could survive nuclear blasts were well known. <br>
<br>
Question 3: The wake effect?<br>
        Oh yes, baby. Anything that gets close to a pulsing Orion will be in deep kaka. We do not know the exact extent of an Orion’s EMP (that research is still classified. We do know that Pulse units will be relatively low yield, and would probably be made to minimize EMP effects. This is all theory and conjecture on our parts). Orion’s will have to have clear, predetermined flight paths when near Earth and/or other inhabited areas.<br>
<br>
Question 4: What if aliens get nuclear technology from us? <br>
        And what if a race of genetically altered tomatoes rise up and conquer the human race? The question is pointless supposition. First, let us find some aliens and then we can argue about the morality of allowing them access to our technologies. <br>
<br>
Question 5: Interstellar speed?<br>
        As envisioned by the original project scientist, Orion would make a poor starship. Its fuel use would be extravagant (though paltry compared to the chemical torches we currently use), and its speed less than relativistic. Orion does, however, make an excellent interplanetary craft for carrying humans. Ironically, its best feature may be that it lowers the crew’s exposure to radiation! Deep space is lethally radioactive, and the faster you can get from point to point, the less exposure you suffer. The radiation released from the pulses would be insignificant. <br>
<br>
Question 6: Shouldn’t we wait for a better technology?<br>
        No. You may be right, but if you wait until we develop warp drive, you might be waiting until the last star goes out. If we do develop a superior technology, great- wonderful. But, we may never develop it. Look at Fusion power- for the last fifty years it has been just twenty years away! Besides, you learn more by doing than by dreaming (not to put dreaming down).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Edited to reflect Mauk2 had answered Question 1. My bad.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"><p>
