<br>
I don't quite know where to begin. You have the concepts of reactor physics so twisted up and confused that I have trouble getting my arms around them. Lets deal with your more important errors.<br>
<br>
First, I think I detect where you initially (and fatally) fell of the rails. You are laboring under a complete misunderstanding of reactor accidents.<br>
It was in your INITIAL post way up the thread. All your other errors of fact and logic flowed from your confusion.<br>
<br>
Here is where it is demonstrated:<br>
You pointed out the Chernobyl accident released &quot;100 million curies, or 4 x 10^18 becquerels.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fine<br>
<br>
Here is where you blew it:<br>
<br>
You did not understand the meaning of your own quote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A more conservative estimate of the release is between 3 and 8 percent of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> total activity</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of the core<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Notice what you said (but did not understand) -- NOT 3 to 5 percent of the MASS of  the core, but 3 to 5 percent of the ACTIVITY of the core!<br>
<br>
Yes, Chernoble dispersed ~6 tons of core material (unfortunately), but that contributed almost NOTHING to the 100,000,000 curies released (other than as a passive carrier for some of the fission products as it flew out)<br>
The bulk radiation was in the ~FISSION PRODUCTS~. <br>
The whole mass of those were a few ~KILOGRAMS~. It would fit in your hand. <br>
<br>
In an accident, the bulk of the high activity fission products &quot;boil out&quot;. There is no need for the massive core to be dispesred (although it may, adding actinides and other nasties. An exploding or reentering booster would do that also)<br>
<br>
Note your error.<br>
This is were you crashed and burned:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have stated in my first post that Chernobyl, ONE REACTOR, released conservatively 9,500 kilograms of intensely radioactive core material. (I will keep it simple and stick to weight released, becquerels make my head hurt.)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->You continued down the wrong track here:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So, assume 19 times 9500 kilograms of radioactive materials are released by a PARTIAL release of one nations reactors. This is a total of 180,500 kilograms of CORE material, the most active stuff imaginable.<br>
<br>
Please explain in detail the scenario where a single nuclear powered heavy-lift booster could release 180,500 kilos of core material. (It'd have to be one BIG mother.  )<br>
<br>
Facts. They're a bear.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->And here discussing reactor rockets:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A reactor has 100 kilos of fuel. <br>
<br>
A booster also has 100 kilos of fuel. <br>
<br>
In ten years, the reactor reaches 50 percent burnup, so there are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 50 kilos or so of fission byproducts in the core.<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  <br>
<br>
In an hour, the booster reaches burnup of 50 percent, and amazingly enough, there are 50 kilos or so of fission byproducts in its co</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Do you see where you erred? <br>
<br>
Everything you wrote was completely off-the-mark<br>
