<br>
I wouldn't worry about decontaminating the craft, or repairing radiation damage or comulative stress on some parts of it. Use the parts of the engine which take the worst punishment until you can't guarantee their safety (with several layers of safety thrown in) and then jettison them.<br>
 If the pusher plate has too much neutron damage, then detach it, attach a solar sail and navigation beacon, and let it drop into the Sun (or stockpile it, until we can). By that time, it's made the effort a few tens of billion dollars, so I won't begrudge the waste of some alumunum, steel, or concrete.<br>
<br>
The wake threat is too inconsequential and obvious to waste time on. Don't fire the thing off when it might hurt something. Period. End of topic. (We've already heard about the threat of the blasts of an Orion ship throwing asteroids out of their orbits, and increasing the threat to Earth...<br>
<br>
By suggesting we wait for a better technology, you've strayed directly into my favorite trap.<br>
 Until we invent something else, or perfect Penning traps and antiproton production (which still might not satisfy the appetite some seem to have for a tasteful, graceful, neat &amp; tidy interplanetary engine), or any number of other advances which nobody can definitely guarantee we'll get, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> there is nothing better</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Why wait? Any better arguments against it?<br>
<br>
Good old dumb, brute force, crude &amp; ugly Orion (blowing off a few kilos of weapons-grade fissionables per bang) is the peak - the pinnacle of human endevors.<br>
 Straight-forward engineering along lines we've got person-centuries of experience with provides us with an interplanetary travel engine which is unbeatable. It also gives us a convenient way to permanently and finally dispose of plutonium which has -one way or another- been enriched to the point where it can be used to make a bomb <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (cough-breeders-cough)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Make money providing rapid, robust interplanetary trael, and make more money selling disposal services to the solar system's nuclear utilities! Maybe at least it would provide a handy way to lower fuel costs...<br>
<br>
Until you can guarantee a particular sort of technical revolution, anyway.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; These are only my scientific arguments mind you. I have my<br>
own set of moral objections to it as well</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Were you honestly worried about us giving nuclear technology to aliens we may encounter? Is that the extent of your &quot;moral&quot; objections? The old stupid hollywood &quot;Prime Directive&quot;, and pulling poor aliens into the nuclear age before they were ready?<br>
<br>
I was honestly hoping we'd hear something new -well, that is a new one, but not a challenging one.<br>
