<br>
I will quote from the book, Project Orion (p. 2), this is describing the launch of the most discussed size, a 4000 ton class Orion:<br>
<br>
&quot;The first 200 explosions, fired at 1/2 second intervals, with a total yield equivalent to 100 kilotons, would lift the ship from sea level to 125,000 feet. 600 more explosions, gradually increasing in yield to 5 kilotons each, would loft the ship into a 300 mile orbit around the earth.&quot;<br>
<br>
So, 100 kiloton <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> total</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> expended to reach 125,000 feet, followed by a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> gradual increase</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to 5 kiloton each to reach a 300 mile orbit.  Even if we assume that each of the 600 were 5 kiloton <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> each</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  and add in the 100 k to reach 125,000 feet, we come up with a total yield expended of 3.1 megatons... much less than the 20 kiloton x 400 pulses = 8 megatons you've quoted.<br>
