Actually, I am pretty familiar with reactor accidents.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   And in this instance, I think I am still &quot;on the rails,&quot;  its just that those rails don't go where you think they do.<br>
<br>
Yes, you are correct!   The total radiation release from even Chernobyl, the classic &quot;worst case scenario&quot; of radiation incidents is only a few kilograms.  (5 is a good ballpark.)  You would not believe how hard it is to get people to understand that simple fact.  <br>
<br>
I am pleased that we have come to an agreement on this FACT (ooooh, that WORD again!) so quickly.<br>
<br>
Why am I pleased?  I have lost this argument, haven't I?  <br>
<br>
Ahhhh, no.  You see, what I am arguing is that the additional risk of radiation release from using powerful NTR boosters is incrementally very small.  Chernobyl is the WORST CASE scenario, seen from my perspective in this debate.  Which makes it the BEST CASE scenario seen from your perspecive in this debate.<br>
<br>
I am perfectly willing to give you your best case.  Hey, facts are facts, and you will use them to your advantage.<br>
<br>
Now, however, I will present models more in my favor.  We will see if I am persuasive.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Follow my train of thought, please.  (Yes, it is a pun on the rails thingy.  Leave me alone.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
Devices which use nuclear reactions may be broadly classed by their power density and speed of reaction.  <br>
<br>
At the lowest end are the medical machines used in radiation therapy.   They perform very little fission and do so very slowly over time.<br>
<br>
Slightly more powerful on the scale are solid state power generators such as are used on space probes.  They produce low levels of reactions, but do so constantly for extremely long periods of time.<br>
<br>
Next come commercial nuclear reactors.  They perform very many fissions, but do so at fairly low power densities and over very long periods of time, years or longer.<br>
<br>
Next on the continuum come experimental, test, and special purpose reactors.  Many of them work very slowly, but many of them have power densities much higher than commercial plants.  Their operational times vary widely as well, from minutes to years.<br>
<br>
Next on the continuum come NTR's.  NTR's produce VERY high power densities and produce MANY fissions, but operate for short periods of time, rarely for more than hours at a time.<br>
<br>
At the top of the line in terms of power density are nuclear bombs.  Their power density is colossal, but they typically only operate for milliseconds at best.<br>
<br>
Now, remember, the issue at hand here is risk.  We have agreed already that the RATE of the reaction has little to do with the &quot;fallout&quot; produced.  (I will ignore issues of &quot;fallout&quot; composition, bioactivity, takeup, dispersal, secondary activation, and half life.  I am not writing a book here.)<br>
<br>
In other words, a commericial reactor working for a year, a NTR working for 10 minutes, and a bomb working for a microsecond, all produce essentially the same risk if the reaction products are allowed to escape.  ( The crucial difference is that the reactor and the NTR are usually designed to contain their reaction products, while the bomb obviously is not.)<br>
<br>
I mentioned earlier  a hypothetical case involving a reactor with 100 kilos of fuel, producing 50 kilos of fission fragments in a year.  Then an NTR with 100 kilos of fuel producing 50 kilos of fission fragments in an hour.   To those let me add a nuclear bomb, with 100 kilos of fuel, producing 50 kilos of fission fragments in a microsecond.  All have the same risk, at least from fallout.<br>
<br>
So far, it seems to be going badly for me, doesn't it.  Here I am, comparing my beloved nuclear booster to a bomb.  But the key of my argument lies in the mitigation of the risk.<br>
<br>
Reactors operate safely for thousands of days.  Therefore, any accidents which happen often catch us completely &quot;off guard.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Bombs, by definition, NEVER operate safely.  Therefore, it is very common to see extraordinary precautions taken before they are operated at all.<br>
<br>
I will postulate, based on the decades of experience of the US space program, that an NTR powered booster would be treated much more like a bomb than a powerplant.  IE, before any use, extensive precautions would be taken.<br>
<br>
In other words, the risk would be mitigated.<br>
<br>
Now, how effective is this risk mitigation?<br>
<br>
Lets see.  We have just examined Chernobyl fairly closely, a classic example of the &quot;unexpected&quot; accident with very low levels of risk mitigation in place.  As I expected, that incident makes nuclear look pretty darn bad.<br>
<br>
For a whole series of examples of the other side of the spectrum, lets look at the  series of nuclear test explosions conducted in the 1950's in the Pacific.  (Before you cry foul, I will point out that YOU are the one who posted the picture of the NTR blowing up so messily.)<br>
<br>
The first major &quot;deliberate accident&quot; was the Ivy Mike test, conducted 11/1/52.  This test resulted in the release of 465 kilos of fission products, in essence DWARFING the release we have agreed upon happened at Chernobyl.  Nobody died.  Nobody was even hurt.   Risk mitigation scores a win!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The next &quot;deliberate accident&quot; was the Castle Bravo test, conducted 3/1/54.  This &quot;oopsy&quot; resulted in the release of 588 kilos of fission products, even more than the first one!  This was the worst radiological accident in US history, with 1 confirmed fatality and more than 87 cases of heavy radiation exposure.  Due to this poor result, for the rest of these tests even MORE stringent safety precautions were emplaced.  Now, compare this to Chernobyl, with 31+ direct deaths from the release of about 1 percent as much &quot;fallout.&quot;  Despite the loss of life, I still class this as a major win for risk mitigation, especially compared to Chernobyl.<br>
<br>
The next &quot;deliberate accident,&quot; with the new safety measures in place, was Castle Romeo, conducted on 3/27/54.   Note the long cleanup time that was required between these two events, a whopping 26 days.  Risk mitigation is a good thing!  Castle Romeo resulted in the release 412 kilograms of Uranium fission fragments.  Nobody died, nobody hurt.  Looking good so far for risk mitigation with the new rules in place.<br>
<br>
The next &quot;deliberate accident&quot; was Castle Union, conducted on 3-26-54.  Note that this test was only one day seperated from the test cited above!  Castle Union released 294 kilos of uranium fission products.  No deaths, no injuries.<br>
<br>
The last of this series of &quot;deliberate accidents&quot; was Castle Yankee, conducted on 5-5-54.  It released 412 kg of uranium fragments.  No deaths, no injuries.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, for those keeping score in the bleachers:  5 total radiation releases, spread over 18 months.  4 of them happened in barely one two month period of time.   They released 2,171 kilograms of FISSION PRODUCTS, compared to an estimated 5 at Chernobyl.  One person died, 87 were injured, and safety measures were improved during the series of tests.<br>
<br>
<br>
Simply put, risk mitigation WORKS.  Nobody is saying that NTR's used as boosters are risk free.  Conversely, every time you swallow there is a risk you will choke to death on your own saliva.  We cannot become paralyzed by irrational fears.<br>
<br>
I will readily say that it is HIGHLY unlikely that there would ever be a series of accidents using NTR's that would exceed or even approach the release of radiation that has already happened and has been successfully dealt with.  The world did not die in the 50's.  <br>
<br>
Would you care to dispute this assertion?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
NOTE: Most of the data for this section was taken from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.milnet.com/milnet/nukeweap/Nfaq8.html"> this site. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->   It is an excellent and often sobering read, I highly recommend it.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  What design have you ever seen that uses less then 90% enrichment?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, yes, here's one of my FAVORITES.  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.npl.washington.edu/AV/altvw56.html"> This proposed design </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is why I think the Orion concept has seen its day.  I recommend you give it a look, it is a very interesting idea.  It has its challenges, make no mistake, but it has great potential I think.  So, what designs have YOU seen that use more than 90 percent?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, I keep promising to post my thoughts on a NTR powered SSTO, I swear I will try to do that in the next few days.  Yales is keeping me busy defending my points.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
